{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_019KHfTLsTuYY7xn8GLTmzv1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is asking me to write a test plan for a software engineering issue. I need to analyze 5 behaviors and determine:\n1. The minimum test level needed to catch a real failure\n2. A test description\n3. Whether the plan is consistent (the test description matches the level)\n4. Level probabilities (confidence for each level)\n\nLet me think through each behavior carefully.\n\n**Behavior 1: TSP heuristic produces route no more than 1.5x optimal for ≤20 stops**\n\nKey questions:\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a pure mock miss this? Yes! If I mock the heuristic to always return a \"good\" route, I won't catch when the real heuristic is worse than 1.5x. The actual algorithmic performance is what matters.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/subprocess/network here - it's computation.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking would completely hide algorithmic failures.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n- What's the failure boundary? The failure is in the algorithm itself. I need to run the real TSP algorithm and measure its output against the optimal. This is Unit-level (one function), but I need to verify the actual algorithm behavior, not mock it.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. The question is \"what test infrastructure is needed to catch a real failure?\" \n\nA real failure would be: the heuristic produces a route worse than 1.5x optimal. To catch this:\n- I need real inputs (various 5-20 stop problems)\n- I need to run the REAL heuristic (not mocked)\n- I need to compute or know the optimal solution\n- I need to verify the ratio\n\nThis is Unit-level because:\n- It's one function boundary\n- No I/O, no external services\n- Pure computation\n\nThe test would be: generate known TSP problems, compute optimal (brute force for small sizes, or use known benchmarks), run the heuristic, verify distance ratio. \n\nSince we're testing the actual algorithm directly without mocks, and the test data can be generated in-memory using synthetic cases or known benchmarks, this stays at Unit level. Confidence: Unit 0.85, Integration 0.15, System 0.0, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n\n**Behavior 2: Time window estimates computed correctly from distance and speed**\n\nKey questions:\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this? If I mock the distance calculator and speed lookup, the test would pass even if the formula is wrong. But the formula itself is deterministic: time = distance / speed. This is pure arithmetic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No I/O, no external APIs needed for the calculation itself.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If I mock distance between stops, I can't verify that the distance calculation integrates correctly with the time window calculation.\n- What's the failure boundary? The formula implementation and its integration with distance calculations.\n\nThis could be Unit (just verify the formula works) or Integration (verify distances are calculated, then used in time window calculation).\n\nTo catch a real failure, I need real or deterministic mock stops/coordinates, then run the actual distance calculation and time window calculation to verify the result. The key decision is whether to mock the distance calculation or run the real one—if I mock it, I lose confidence that the two pieces work together correctly.\n\nThe risk isn't just in the formula itself, but in how distance data flows into it. Unit testing catches formula errors, but integration testing catches unit mismatches (miles vs kilometers) or incorrect data passing. Since the instructions emphasize catching real failures with minimum infrastructure, I should lean toward integration testing to verify both the formula and its interaction with distance calculations work as expected.\n\nConfidence: Unit 0.3\n\n, Integration 0.7, System 0.0, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n\nFor the shift-hours validator, the core logic is straightforward arithmetic—checking if total time exceeds remaining hours and calculating the excess. I can test this at the Unit level with mocked time inputs since there's no I/O or external dependencies. The main failure points are the comparison operator, excess calculation, and return format. However, since the validator depends on accurate time estimates from the previous behavior, testing it in isolation might miss integration issues where incorrect time calculations propagate through to the validation decision.\n\nConfidence: Unit 0.8, Integration 0.2, System 0.0, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n\n**Behavior 4: When one address fails geocoding, skip it and optimize the rest, reporting skipped addresses**\n\nThe geocoding API failure handling is different—mocking the API would hide real failure scenarios. I need to test against the actual geocoding service to verify the system properly handles failures, skips bad addresses, continues optimizing the remaining ones, and reports which addresses were skipped. This requires a real HTTP call to the geocoding API, or at minimum a test server that can simulate API failures. The error handling, filtering logic, and reporting all need to work together correctly.\n\nTesting with a mocked geocoding API that returns errors would be Integration-level (multiple modules working together with controlled dependencies). Testing against the real geocoding API would be System-level. I think Integration is sufficient—mock the geocoding API to return failure for one address and verify the rest of the behavior.\n\nConfidence: Unit 0.0, Integration 0.7, System 0.3, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n\nFor duplicate address consolidation, the key is understanding how duplicates are actually identified. If detection relies on string comparison of addresses, this is straightforward Unit testing. If it depends on comparing geocoded coordinates, I'd need mocked geocoding in the test. The real question is whether addresses get normalized before comparison, which could require additional infrastructure. This feels like Unit-level work, but the definition of \"duplicate\" matters—whether it's based on the raw address string or the geocoded location.\n\nFor the TSP heuristic, the algorithm itself is what's being tested. I can generate synthetic coordinates and verify the heuristic produces acceptable results without any external dependencies or real geocoding. The test would involve creating known instances with 5, 10, and 20 stops, computing optimal or near-optimal route lengths, then checking whether the heuristic stays within acceptable bounds.\n\nFor time window estimation, this requires testing the full pipeline from distance to time calculation. Mocking distance values would mask failures in how distance feeds into time calculations, unit conversions, or speed lookups. The integration between these components is where bugs typically hide.\n\nThe test should construct a route with known stops and coordinates, provide mocked speed values for different road types, then verify each segment correctly computes distance from coordinates, retrieves the appropriate speed, and applies the formula time = distance / speed with proper unit handling. This confirms the three components work together correctly.\n\nFor the shift-hours validator, most of the logic is self-contained and doesn't depend on other modules, making it primarily a Unit-level concern. The validator is a pure comparison: if total_time > remaining_hours, reject and return excess = total_time - remaining_hours. This is a single function with numeric inputs and a boolean/number output. No I/O, no external systems.\n\n**Why not higher**: The validation logic itself is simple. Failures would be in the comparison operator or arithmetic, which are deterministic and testable at Unit level. (Note: the input times should be correctly calculated per Behavior 2, but that's a separate concern.)\n\n**Test description**: Provide pre-calculated total times and remaining shift hours. Call the validator with cases: (1) total_time < remaining_hours (should accept), (2) total_time == remaining_hours (should accept), (3) total_time > remaining_hours (should reject and return exact excess amount). Verify the validator returns correct boolean and excess value.\n\n**Plan consistent**: Yes. Pure function with numeric inputs matches Unit level.\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 4: Geocoding Failure Handling\n\n**Minimum level**: Integration (0.0 Unit, 0.7 Integration, 0.3 System, 0.0 Agentic, 0.0 Workflow)\n\n**Why Integration**: Handling a real or simulated geocoding API failure requires multiple components working together—the geocoding call, error handling, filtering, reporting, and optimization on the reduced set. A Unit test with a mocked geocoding function would miss integration bugs in the error-handling pipeline. An Integration test mocks the geocoding API to fail for one address, connects the components, and confirms the service handles the error correctly and reports it properly.\n\n**Why not Unit**: Isolated Unit tests wouldn't surface failures in how error recovery integrates with the rest of the system.\n\n**Why not System**: A mocked geocoding API in an Integration test provides sufficient coverage.\n\n**Test description**: Configure the geocoding mock to succeed for N-1 addresses and return no results for 1 address. Call the service with N addresses. Verify: (1) the failed address is skipped, (2) optimization runs on the remaining N-1 addresses, (3) the service reports which address failed, (4) the returned route excludes the skipped address.\n\n**Plan consistent**: Yes. Multiple modules (geocoding, error handling, filtering, reporting) wired together with a mock API confirms Integration level.\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 5: Duplicate Address Consolidation\n\n**Minimum level**: Unit (0.7 Unit, 0.3 Integration, 0.0 System, 0.0 Agentic, 0.0 Workflow)\n\n**Why Unit**: Deduplication and consolidation is a single function that takes a list of addresses and combines duplicates. If duplicates are identified by direct address string comparison, it's pure in-process logic with no I/O.\n\n**Why could be Integration**: If duplicate detection compares geocoded coordinates (requiring a geocoding call) or normalizes addresses through an external service, the level would be higher. But with direct address string comparison, Unit is appropriate.\n\n**Test description**: Pass a list of addresses containing 2-3 duplicates with distinct delivery items for each. Call the deduplication logic. Verify: (1) duplicate addresses merge into a single stop, (2) items from duplicates are combined (quantities summed or lists concatenated), (3) no address appears twice in the output.\n\n**Plan consistent**: Yes (assuming string comparison for duplicates). Pure list processing with in-memory data aligns with Unit level. If geocoding is involved, this becomes Integration.\n\n---\n\nNow I need to structure these into the required JSON format.\n\nActually, I should reconsider behavior 4. The key question is whether this uses a real HTTP call to a geocoding API (System) or a mock of the geocoding API (Integration). The instructions emphasize \"minimum test infrastructure needed to catch a real failure\"—a real failure being the service's inability to handle geocoding errors correctly. To catch this, I can either mock the geocoding API to return an error and test error handling (Integration), or call the real API with a bad address (System). Integration is the minimum because it tests the error handling logic without relying on the real API's availability or behavior. System would be over-specification.\n\nSo Integration for behavior 4 is the right choice.\n\n---\n\nI should also reconsider behavior 1 regarding TSP heuristic performance up to 1.5x optimal. Computing the optimal solution for instances up to 20 nodes is challenging—brute force TSP is O(n!), making 20! computationally infeasible. I'd need precomputed benchmarks or a more efficient algorithm to establish the optimal baseline.\n\nUsing precomputed benchmarks stored in test data remains Unit-level testing. Even if I compute optimal solutions via dynamic programming or use a real TSP benchmark dataset like TSPLIB, that's still Unit since it's just test data without external dependencies. I could also test with a large corpus of synthetic problems to ensure the heuristic performs well across many instances, which is still Unit (many in-memory test cases). I'll stick with Unit, confidence 0.85.\n\n---\n\nNow reconsidering behavior 2: should I test time window estimation at Unit or Integration level?\n\nThe behavior requires estimating time from distance between consecutive stops and configured average speed. This involves distance calculation, speed configuration, and time calculation. If distance calculation is a separate module, Integration testing makes sense to verify the full pipeline works together. Re-reading the requirement—consecutive stops, computing distances between them, looking up speed for the road type, then calculating time as distance divided by speed—suggests I need to test the complete flow to ensure all components integrate properly.\n\nRegarding Agentic level: this would only apply if results depend on real LLM non-determinism or ML model calls. TSP heuristics are typically deterministic (nearest neighbor, ant colony optimization), so Unit level suffices. Even randomized approaches like genetic algorithms can be tested with fixed seeds. Route optimization, address parsing, and delivery estimation are unlikely to involve LLM calls unless the implementation explicitly uses one, which would be unusual for these core functions.\n\nI need to verify the probability distributions sum to 1.0 across all five levels for each behavior, then finalize the JSON with clear plan_consistent_note explanations for each test.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13467,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13467},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90d35102-f4b0-4fac-914a-df1f0d3cfe80","uuid":"0be301e2-baa1-4207-b84f-0d2bae2b76a1"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_019KHfTLsTuYY7xn8GLTmzv1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I'll analyze each behavior to determine the minimum test infrastructure needed to catch a real failure.\n\n## Analysis\n\n**Behavior 1: TSP Heuristic Performance**\nThe failure is in the algorithm itself—the heuristic producing routes worse than 1.5x optimal. This is testable entirely in-process with synthetic test cases and precomputed (or brute-force-computed for small instances) optimal solutions. No external I/O, no mocking of the heuristic itself. Pure computation.\n\n**Behavior 2: Time Window Estimation** \nThe failure could hide in the integration between distance calculation and time calculation—wrong units (miles vs. km), incorrect speed lookup, or formula error. Testing distance in isolation misses integration bugs. Need to wire distance → speed → time together to catch realistic failures.\n\n**Behavior 3: Shift-Hours Validator**\nThe validator is a pure comparison function: if `total_time > remaining_hours`, reject and return `excess`. Failures would be in the operator or arithmetic, which are deterministic and testable at Unit level with numeric inputs. (The upstream time calculations are covered by Behavior 2.)\n\n**Behavior 4: Geocoding Failure Handling**\nThe service must handle a geocoding API failure gracefully—skip the failed address, optimize the remaining ones, report the skipped address. A Unit test with a mocked geocoding function misses error-handling integration bugs. Minimum is Integration: mock the API to return failure for one address, wire error handling + filtering + reporting + optimization together, verify the full pipeline.\n\n**Behavior 5: Duplicate Consolidation**\nThis is a single function processing a list: detect duplicate addresses (likely by string comparison), merge them, and combine delivery items. Pure in-process list logic with no I/O. (If duplicates are detected by geocoded coordinates instead, it would be Integration—but string comparison is the likely design.)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13467,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13467},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90d35102-f4b0-4fac-914a-df1f0d3cfe80","uuid":"54319dd3-02d5-43ce-a040-ae9d076dac0b"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_019KHfTLsTuYY7xn8GLTmzv1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018csdv2TMqoEGtAvhqB1hNo","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure is in the algorithm itself—the heuristic implementation. This is pure computation with no external dependencies. Generate synthetic test instances (5, 10, 20 stops with known coordinates), compute or precompute optimal solutions, run the heuristic, and verify the distance ratio is ≤1.5. No I/O, no subprocess, no external API calls needed.","test_description":"Create TSP instances with 5, 10, and 20 stops using synthetic coordinates. For each instance, compute the optimal route length (via precomputed benchmark, dynamic programming, or brute force for small sizes). Run the heuristic and measure the resulting route distance. Verify that heuristic_distance / optimal_distance ≤ 1.5 for all test instances.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test is purely computational with in-memory test data. No mocking of the heuristic—testing the real algorithm. Matches Unit level (single function boundary, no I/O).","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.15,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The behavior couples distance calculation with time window calculation. Failures could hide in the integration: wrong units (miles vs. km, seconds vs. hours), incorrect speed lookup, or formula misapplication. Testing distance in isolation (mocked) would miss real failures in the distance→speed→time pipeline. Need to wire distance calculation, speed lookup, and time computation together.","test_description":"Create a route with known consecutive stops (synthetic coordinates). Provide or mock the average speed for each road type. For each segment, verify: (1) distance is calculated from coordinates, (2) average speed is looked up for the road type, (3) time is computed as distance/speed in correct units (e.g., hours from km and km/h), (4) result matches expected values. Test with multiple segments and road types.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires multiple modules wired together (distance calculation, speed configuration lookup, time formula). Cannot mock distance and still catch real failures. Confirms Integration level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.7,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The validator is a single pure comparison function: if total_time > remaining_hours, reject and return excess. Failures would be in the comparison operator (>, >=) or in the arithmetic (subtraction). This is deterministic, testable with numeric inputs, no I/O, no external systems.","test_description":"Call the shift-hours validator with pre-calculated total times and remaining shift hours. Test cases: (1) total_time < remaining_hours → should accept route, (2) total_time == remaining_hours → should accept route, (3) total_time > remaining_hours → should reject route and return excess amount equal to (total_time - remaining_hours). Verify both the boolean accept/reject and the excess value are correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Pure function logic with numeric inputs and arithmetic output. No dependencies on other modules, no I/O. The test validates the validator's logic in isolation, which is appropriate at Unit level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.2,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The behavior spans multiple modules: geocoding API call, error handling, address filtering, report generation, and optimization on the reduced set. A Unit test with a mocked geocoding function might pass even if error recovery, filtering, or reporting logic is broken. A real failure would involve the integration of these steps. Minimum is Integration: mock the geocoding API to return failure for one address, wire the components together, and verify the entire error-handling pipeline works.","test_description":"Mock the geocoding API to return success for N-1 addresses and no results for 1 address. Call the service with a list of N addresses. Verify: (1) the service skips the failed address and does not include it in optimization, (2) optimization proceeds correctly on the remaining N-1 addresses, (3) the service reports which address(es) were skipped and why (no geocoding results), (4) the returned route does not contain the skipped stop, (5) delivery items for the skipped address are handled correctly (dropped or reported).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires mocking the geocoding API and wiring error handling, filtering, reporting, and optimization together. Cannot test error handling in isolation without missing integration bugs. Confirms Integration level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Deduplication and consolidation is a single function processing a list: detect duplicate addresses (by string comparison), merge them into one stop, and combine delivery items. This is pure in-process logic with no I/O, no external systems. Failures would be in duplicate detection, item consolidation, or output structure—all testable at Unit level.","test_description":"Provide a list of addresses with 2-3 duplicates, each with distinct delivery items (e.g., quantities, item types). Call the deduplication and consolidation function. Verify: (1) each unique address appears exactly once in the output, (2) delivery items from duplicate entries are correctly combined (e.g., quantities summed or lists concatenated), (3) no address is visited twice, (4) address metadata (coordinates, type) is preserved correctly for consolidated stops.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test is pure list processing logic with in-memory data. No external dependencies, no I/O. Assumes duplicates are detected by address string comparison (not by geocoded coordinates). Matches Unit level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.3,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13467,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13467},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90d35102-f4b0-4fac-914a-df1f0d3cfe80","uuid":"55dd4592-6e96-4fa5-ad5c-6aac7fc70fb5"}
